Diagnosis

TypeScript compile failed while running the build (line 64), causing Netlify to stop the build (line 73).
Specific compiler errors:
line 65: App.tsx(277,42): error TS18048 — "'msg.toolCall.functionCalls' is possibly 'undefined'".
line 66 and line 67: services/geminiService.ts(5,38) and vite.config.ts(5,29): error TS2580 — "Cannot find name 'process'. Do you need to install type definitions for node?"
Cause

The App.tsx error is a strict null/undefined type-safety error: code is accessing msg.toolCall.functionCalls while TypeScript’s type for msg.toolCall allows undefined.
The "Cannot find name 'process'" errors occur because TypeScript does not have Node.js ambient type definitions available during compilation (vite config and service files run in Node context). @types/node (or adding node types in tsconfig) is missing/not included.
Solution

Fix the undefined access in App.tsx
Open App.tsx and locate the offending access around the reported position (line shown in logs: line 65). Either guard for undefined or use optional chaining, for example:
// safer: only use functionCalls if toolCall exists
const functionCalls = msg.toolCall?.functionCalls;

// or if you must iterate:
if (msg.toolCall?.functionCalls) {
  // use msg.toolCall.functionCalls safely here
}
If you are certain toolCall is always defined at runtime and want to assert that to the compiler (use with caution):
const functionCalls = msg.toolCall!.functionCalls;
Choose the fix that matches runtime guarantees: prefer checks/optional chaining unless you can guarantee non-null.

Provide Node type definitions so TypeScript recognizes process
Install @types/node as a dev dependency in the project root:
npm install --save-dev @types/node
Ensure the package is added to package.json (verify that the dev dependency appears in package.json after install).

Add or update tsconfig.json to include Node types (in compilerOptions). If you already have a "types" array, add "node"; otherwise add the full snippet:

{
  "compilerOptions": {
    // ...existing options...
    "types": ["node"]
  }
}
If you want to limit types only for files that need Node types (e.g., vite.config.ts), you can also add a triple-slash reference at the top of that file:
/// <reference types="node" />
Rebuild and deploy
Commit your changes (App.tsx fix, package.json and package-lock.json updates, tsconfig.json) and push to the repo. Run the build locally to verify:
npm run build
Once successful locally, push and let Netlify rebuild.
Notes

The failure originated in the TypeScript step invoked by your build command (tsc && vite build) — see line 64 and the reported errors at line 65–line 67.
If you change Node versions on Netlify later, follow Netlify’s docs for changing Node versions: https://docs.netlify.com/configure-builds/manage-dependencies/#node-js-and-javascript

